body:
Hi ,
      I am extending React.Component to define components in scala.js 

``` scala
class Test extends ReactComponent { //scala.js code
  val displayName = "Test"
  def render() = React.createElement("div")
}
```

in react dev tools i am seeing No Display Name for all my components, for some reason scala.js output not getting name from  this function 

``` js
  /**
   * Get a text description of the component that can be used to identify it
   * in error messages.
   * @return {string} The name or null.
   * @internal
   */
  getName: function() {
    var type = this._currentElement.type;
    var constructor = this._instance && this._instance.constructor;
    return (
      type.displayName || (constructor && constructor.displayName) ||
      type.name || (constructor && constructor.name) ||
      null
    );
  },
```

https://github.com/facebook/react/blob/6a92179d6fd6d7c4097f6310a7cefb2c0651287f/src/renderers/shared/reconciler/ReactCompositeComponent.js#L784

is it okay to modify this function to get displayName from instance before i break my head by digging to javascript prototypes constructors .. ? 

the following code works for me.

``` js
  /**
   * Get a text description of the component that can be used to identify it
   * in error messages.
   * @return {string} The name or null.
   * @internal
   */
  getName: function() {
    var type = this._currentElement.type;
    var constructor = this._instance && this._instance.constructor;
    return (
      type.displayName || (constructor && constructor.displayName) ||
      type.name || (constructor && constructor.name) || (this._instance && this._instance.displayName) ||
      null
    );
  },
```
